    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n<meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" />\n<title>SQL Concept Demonstration</title>\n<style>\n  body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 2rem; background: #f0f0f0; }\n  h1 { color: #333; }\n  pre { background: #222; color: #0f0; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 5px; overflow-x: auto; }\n  table { border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 1rem; }\n  th, td { padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border: 1px solid #ccc; }\n  th { background-color: #eee; }\n  .section { background: white; padding: 1rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; border-radius: 8px; box-shadow: 0 0 5px #ccc; }\n</style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <h1>SQL Concept Demonstration</h1>\n  <div class=\"section\">\n    <h2>What is SQL?</h2>\n    <p>\n      <strong>SQL</strong> (Structured Query Language) is a standard language for managing and manipulating databases.\n      It allows you to create, read, update, and delete data in a relational database.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section\">\n    <h2>Sample SQL Table: <code>Employees</code></h2>\n    <p>Imagine a table with employee data:</p>\n    <pre>\nCREATE TABLE Employees (\n  ID INT PRIMARY KEY,\n  Name VARCHAR(100),\n  Department VARCHAR(50),\n  Salary INT\n);\n    </pre>\n    <p>And some sample data:</p>\n    <table>\n      <thead>\n        <tr><th>ID</th><th>Name</th><th>Department</th><th>Salary</th></tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr><td>1</td><td>Alice</td><td>Engineering</td><td>75000</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>2</td><td>Bob</td><td>Marketing</td><td>50000</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>3</td><td>Charlie</td><td>Engineering</td><td>80000</td></tr>\n        <tr><td>4</td><td>Dana</td><td>HR</td><td>60000</td></tr>\n      </tbody>\n    </table>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section\">\n    <h2>Common SQL Queries</h2>\n    <p>Here are a few example SQL queries & their explanations:</p>\n\n    <h3>1. Select all employees</h3>\n    <pre>SELECT * FROM Employees;</pre>\n    <p>This fetches all columns and all rows from the Employees table.</p>\n\n    <h3>2. Select employees in Engineering</h3>\n    <pre>SELECT Name, Salary FROM Employees WHERE Department = 'Engineering';</pre>\n    <p>This fetches only the Name and Salary of employees working in the Engineering department.</p>\n\n    <h3>3. Increase salary by 10% for Marketing department</h3>\n    <pre>UPDATE Employees SET Salary = Salary * 1.1 WHERE Department = 'Marketing';</pre>\n    <p>This updates the salary for Marketing employees by increasing it by 10%.</p>\n\n    <h3>4. Delete employee with ID = 4</h3>\n    <pre>DELETE FROM Employees WHERE ID = 4;</pre>\n    <p>This deletes the employee Dana from the table.</p>\n\n    <h3>5. Aggregate example: Average salary by department</h3>\n    <pre>\nSELECT Department, AVG(Salary) AS AvgSalary\nFROM Employees\nGROUP BY Department;\n    </pre>\n    <p>This calculates the average salary per department.</p>\n\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section\">\n    <h2>Simulating SQL Queries with JavaScript</h2>\n    <p>Below is a simple demonstration of how SQL-like queries can be run on an array of objects (representing table rows) in JavaScript.</p>\n\n    <button onclick=\"runQueries()\">Run SQL Queries Simulation</button>\n\n    <pre id=\"output\"></pre>\n  </div>\n\n  <script>\n    const employees = [\n      {ID: 1, Name: \"Alice\", Department: \"Engineering\", Salary: 75000},\n      {ID: 2, Name: \"Bob\", Department: \"Marketing\", Salary: 50000},\n      {ID: 3, Name: \"Charlie\", Department: \"Engineering\", Salary: 80000},\n      {ID: 4, Name: \"Dana\", Department: \"HR\", Salary: 60000},\n    ];\n\n    function runQueries() {\n      let output = '';\n\n      // 1. SELECT * FROM Employees;\n      output += \"1. SELECT * FROM Employees;\\n\";\n      output += JSON.stringify(employees, null, 2) + \"\\n\\n\";\n\n      // 2. SELECT Name, Salary FROM Employees WHERE Department = 'Engineering';\n      const engineering = employees\n        .filter(emp => emp.Department === 'Engineering')\n        .map(emp => ({Name: emp.Name, Salary: emp.Salary}));\n      output += \"2. SELECT Name, Salary FROM Employees WHERE Department = 'Engineering';\\n\";\n      output += JSON.stringify(engineering, null, 2) + \"\\n\\n\";\n\n      // 3. UPDATE Employees SET Salary = Salary * 1.1 WHERE Department = 'Marketing';\n      const updatedEmployees = employees.map(emp => {\n        if(emp.Department === 'Marketing') {\n          return {...emp, Salary: Math.round(emp.Salary * 1.1)};\n        }\n        return emp;\n      });\n      output += \"3. UPDATE Employees SET Salary = Salary * 1.1 WHERE Department = 'Marketing';\\n\";\n      output += JSON.stringify(updatedEmployees, null, 2) + \"\\n\\n\";\n\n      // 4. DELETE FROM Employees WHERE ID = 4;\n      const afterDeletion = updatedEmployees.filter(emp => emp.ID !== 4);\n      output += \"4. DELETE FROM Employees WHERE ID = 4;\\n\";\n      output += JSON.stringify(afterDeletion, null, 2) + \"\\n\\n\";\n\n      // 5. SELECT Department, AVG(Salary) AS AvgSalary FROM Employees GROUP BY Department;\n      const salaryByDept = afterDeletion.reduce((acc, emp) => {\n        if (!acc[emp.Department]) {\n          acc[emp.Department] = {sum: 0, count: 0};\n        }\n        acc[emp.Department].sum += emp.Salary;\n        acc[emp.Department].count++;\n        return acc;\n      }, {});\n\n      const avgSalaryByDept = Object.entries(salaryByDept).map(([dept, {sum, count}]) => ({\n        Department: dept,\n        AvgSalary: Math.round(sum / count)\n      }));\n\n      output += \"5. SELECT Department, AVG(Salary) AS AvgSalary FROM Employees GROUP BY Department;\\n\";\n      output += JSON.stringify(avgSalaryByDept, null, 2) + \"\\n\\n\";\n\n      document.getElementById('output').textContent = output;\n    }\n  </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
  },
